	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Does anyone know how many free I/O there are on the PowerPak? Perhaps we could come up with a DAC and mixing circuit internal to the PowerPak. Also how many DAC bits are necessary to support the existing sound chips? I'm not sure either if there's enough logic left over for some of the big sound chips.
<br />
<br /><img src="http://img293.imageshack.us/img293/3048/ppakbf4.png" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br />I think it would be OK to distribute a program to patch the official BIOS and join it with a FDS ROM for use with a mapper on the PowerPak.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Mon Aug 25, 2008 8:24 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />If your DAC is mono and clocked over 1 MHz, you really only need one output. You toggle a bit at rates in the hundreds of kilohertz, and then you run the output through a low-pass filter circuit. It's called <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse-density_modulation" class="postlink">pulse-density modulation</a>, and all SACD players use it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


